{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568387"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:14:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:14:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20320"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20320"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.03,0.1,0.09,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13121"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89693"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13121"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73847"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"874"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"30533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32435"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89693"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 29-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of upper abdominal pain. The pain came on suddenly, is moderate in intensity, and has not been associated with nausea, vomiting, or changes in bowel habits. He has never had this pain before and is otherwise in good health. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He does not smoke, drinks beer at weekends, and works as an office manager.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals mild epigastric tenderness but no guarding or rebound tenderness. The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable. A CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately describes the CT findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal examination","Right adrenal neoplasm","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Gallstones","Ectopic kidney"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a normal abdominal examination except for the presence of a kidney located in the pelvis rather than in its normal retroperitoneal position. This finding is consistent with an \u003Cstrong\u003Eectopic kidney\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically a pelvic kidney. This is a congenital anomaly that occurs when a kidney fails to ascend to its normal position during embryonic development. The kidney appears to have normal parenchyma and collecting system, though it is in an abnormal location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal examination\u003C/strong\u003E would show both kidneys in their expected locations in the retroperitoneum. The presence of a kidney in the pelvis is clearly abnormal, though it is likely an incidental finding unrelated to the patient\u0027s presenting symptoms of upper abdominal pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eright adrenal neoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a mass arising from the right adrenal gland, which sits atop the right kidney. The image shows no evidence of an adrenal mass, and the abnormality is clearly a kidney with its characteristic shape and internal architecture located in the pelvis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrointestinal stromal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E (GIST) would appear as a mass arising from the wall of the gastrointestinal tract, typically the stomach or small intestine. GISTs have a different appearance from renal tissue and would not have the characteristic shape and internal architecture of a kidney.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows no evidence of \u003Cstrong\u003Egallstones\u003C/strong\u003E, which would appear as high-density structures within the gallbladder or biliary tree. Gallstones are typically visible as hyperdense foci within the gallbladder lumen on CT, and there is no evidence of this in the provided image.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEctopic kidneys are relatively uncommon, occurring in approximately 1 in 1,000 births. Most remain asymptomatic throughout life and are discovered incidentally during imaging studies performed for unrelated reasons, as in this case. The most common locations for ectopic kidneys are the pelvis and the lower abdomen. While ectopic kidneys generally function normally, they may be more susceptible to certain complications such as hydronephrosis, stones, or infections due to abnormal drainage. In this patient, the ectopic kidney is likely an incidental finding and not the cause of his acute abdominal pain, which requires further evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pelvic kidneys are a congenital anomaly where the kidney fails to ascend to its normal position during embryonic development.","Ectopic kidneys are usually asymptomatic and found incidentally on imaging studies.","CT imaging is an effective modality for identifying renal anomalies and distinguishing them from other abdominal or pelvic masses."],"references":["Eid S, Iwanaga J, Loukas M, et al. Pelvic Kidney: A Review of the Literature. Cureus. 2018; 10:e2775."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73847"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20320"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21741"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21741"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xDpbLwkgtkdI0scHbLmnUxKaha7gNc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xDpbLwkgtkdI0scHbLmnUxKaha7gNc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":730,"height":730}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/73847"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-10T16:21:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-01T23:25:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13121"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89693"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emed